      <hedline>
        <hl1>Beach Access And Property Taxes</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Save LBI Beaches Advocacy Group officer Mary DeRogatis letter on December 10 editorial on broadening beach access on Long Beach Island, NJ</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Broadening Beach Access'' (editorial, Dec. 10): You describe some residents of Long Beach Island as ''vehemently opposed'' to proposed regulations for beach access. I am one of those residents, and my opposition is based on how these regulations would affect property taxes.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Broadening Beach Access'' (editorial, Dec. 10): You describe some residents of Long Beach Island as ''vehemently opposed'' to proposed regulations for beach access. I am one of those residents, and my opposition is based on how these regulations would affect property taxes.</p>
        <p>The accessways, restrooms and parking mandated by the state would strain local coffers. Any progress legislators made in reducing taxes would be offset by executive branch regulations.</p>
        <p>Mary DeRogatis  Long Beach Township</p>
        <p>The writer is an officer of Save LBI Beaches Advocacy Group.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
